{
  "text": "Nowadays, breast cancer is the most commonly diagnosed life-threatening cancer in women and remains the leading cause of death by cancer among women, with 1.7 million cases and 521,900 deaths estimated in 2012. [CITATION_1] Indeed, breast cancer accounts for 25% of all cancer cases and 15% of all cancer deaths in women. [CITATION_2] In a developing country, about 55.6% of all cancer cases and 62.1% of deaths are due to breast cancer. [CITATION_3] Interestingly, breast cancer incidence rates vary substantially by world region. [CITATION_4] Although there is a lower incidence of breast cancer in the North Africa region compared to Western countries, the global picture in Northern Africa is dynamically changing. [CITATION_5] Morocco, for example, is currently a country in epidemiological transition, and the breast cancer is becoming one of the main public health problems. [CITATION_6] The rising incidence tendency in low-and middleincome countries is mainly due to increases of risk factors caused by economic development and urbanization. Many factors among others include overweight and obesity, physical inactivity, earlier age at menarche, delayed childbearing, and/or having fewer children, as well as shorter duration of breastfeeding. [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] Early screening, diagnosis, and management, together with improved treatments, may explain the international disparities in breast cancer mortality trends. Overall, there was an upward trend in the prevalence of overweight among Moroccan women, which increased over a period of 1 year from 29.0% in 1999 to 47.8% in 2000.",
